ences from your past, present and future.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nEmotional intelligence is making a huge mistake, but learning from it, forgiving yourself, and setting new and higher related-standards below which you will never operate.\n\n- Dr. Jacinta Mpalyenkana, Ph.D, MBA\n|\nYou are my best friend as well as my lover, and I do not know which side of you I enjoy the most. I treasure each side, just as I have treasured our life together.\n\n- Nicholas Sparks, The Notebook\n|\nWhen we are tired, we are attacked by ideas we conquered long ago.\n\n- Friedrich\n|\nAt one time I had given much thought to why men were so very rarely capable of living for an ideal. Now I saw that many, no, all men were capable of dying for one.\n\n- Hermann Hesse, Demian. Die Geschichte von Emil Sinclairs Jugend\n|\nYou are whole today, looking back at fragments of the past. Such a hollow foundation for such a powerful person.\n\n- Hubert\n|\nHow do you knowyou're a girl?I'm wearing a frock.And if you take it off?I get cold, so I putit back on.If I was a boy, I don't know what I'd do.\n\n- Ivor Cutler, Scots Wa' Straw\n|\nForget regret, or life is yours to miss. No other path, no other way, no day but today.\n\n- Jonathan Larson, Rent\n|\nThe thread connecting one person, one event, to another exists only in the imagination.\n\n- Marty\n|\nFor Liza, a greeting is an opportunity to make new friends. For me, it's yet more people I'll have to avoid.\n\n- Ariel Leve, It Could Be Worse, You Could Be Me\n|\nLoving another person is a wonderful thing, and if that love is sincere, no one ends up tossed into a labyrinth. You have to have more faith in yourself.\n\n- Haruki Murakami, Norwegian Wood\n|\nAnd, in the endThe love you takeis equal to the love you make.\n\n- Paul McCartney, The Beatles Illustrated Lyrics\n|\nStep beyond the scopes and limits because a narrow minded person has such boundaries of thinking “I cannot , but I must\n\n- Sunday\n|\nI am heartbroken, but I have been heartbroken before, and this might be the best for which I can hope.\n\n- Lemony Snicket, The End\n|\nBut love, the great narcotic, was the hothouse in which all the selves burst into their fullest bloom...\n\n- Anaïs Nin, The Four-Chambered Heart: V3 in Nin's Continuous Novel\n|\nThis was something they could not take from us - the freedom to imagine, to create new worlds beyond this one.\n\n- Laura McVeigh, Under the Almond Tree\n|\nWine can be a better teacher than ink, and banter is often better than books\n\n- Stephen Fry, The Fry Chronicles\n|\nLive in the present, remember the past, and fear not the future, for it doesn't exist and never shall. There is only now.\n\n- Christopher Paolini, Eldest\n|\nJust go with it', he thought. 'You won't figure out anything if you give in to fear'.\n\n- James\n|\nListen to your fears, they are the doorway to your freedom.\n\n- Catherine\n|\nThe new mythology of love was that it bent to the fashion of the day, obligated to take the shape of doves, lilies, jewels. This is a lie. Love is sometimes as passionate as war.\n\n- Brenna\n|\nDon't be afraid to be successful,and keep in your mind that you don't have another choice “be successful or be successful\n\n- Aymen\n|\nPHOSPHORESCENCE. Now there's a word to lift your hat to... to find that phosphorescence, that light within, that's the genius behind poetry.\n\n- Emily\n|\nFaith and freedom is great, but it gets nowhere without faith in freedom.\n\n- A.E.\n|\nWhere there is a Key, there is yet hope.\n\n- Catherynne M. Valente, The Girl Who Circumnavigated Fairyland in a Ship of Her Own Making\n|\nThe foundation laid in us before was a foundation of thoughts, traditions, and religion of men\n\n- Sunday\n|\nI can manage,' said Frodo. 'I must.\n\n- J.R.R. Tolkien, The Return of the King\n|\nIntegrity without knowledge is weak and useless, and knowledge without integrity is dangerous and dreadful.\n\n- Samuel Johnson, The History of Rasselas, Prince of Abissinia\n|\nThere are some things you can't 